snippet.textDisplay:
I’m all for Mark and Ethan advertising different businesses, but this one is a horrible place to advertise. Okay so let's see.

They have a video on their Facebook of a dog named Aiko showcasing “service dog training”
They place an infant in the dogs back and let the baby climb on Aiko, ride Aiko around and the whole time, the dog is showing incredible signs of stress and being uncomfortable. They are endangering Aiko's health by placing an infant on his back, and not even properly positioned for where weight should be placed on a dog who is cleared for bracing (which is DIRECTLY on the shoulders) and having him move around with that weight (which service dogs DO NOT get trained to do because it can WRECK THEIR SPINES).

They placed an infant near a dog throwing off a TON of stress signals, including whale-eye, excessive licking, and leg-ups. They’re lucky that the dog didn't bite them or the child, and that says more about the dog's inherent temperament than the "training."

The choke chain is NOT being properly used, when walking it's cinched up at all times showing that they’re putting CONSTANT pressure on the dog's trachea and are not appropriately correcting the dog for pulling on the lead (which it's doing to get the fuck away from you and the baby on its back).

And they charge money for this neglectful and dangerous care? No thank you. Disappointed.

snippet.textDisplay: I work at a pet store and the amount of ignorant people that just run up to a strangers dog (service dog or not) is ridiculous. There are parents who let their kids run wildly and the kids just run up to the dogs without asking to pet them. And the amount of adult who do the same thing baffles me. There was a dog in one of our training classes who was learning to slowly trust new people and this asshole guy just walks by and roughly pats the dog on the butt. The dog turned around so fast and almost bit his hand off. The dude got so pissed and said "that dog shouldn't be here. It needs to be put down." Um, no sir. You just need to learn to ask before you pet. It was your own damn fault.

snippet.textDisplay:
Thank you guys so much for taking people with service dogs and the service dogs themselves seriously. So many people exploit the service dog community for their own benefit and it is NOT. SAFE. Thank you for making that clear in this video and showing just how much love, support, and work goes into training and working with a service animal.


For everyone else, if you live in the United States, it is federally legal to ask only the following questions to someone with a service dog:
1) Is the dog a Service Animal required because of a disability?
2) What work or task has the dog been trained to perform?


This is a safe way to ensure the dog is a service animal (some will buy a vest online without going through proper training, which can be very dangerous in public settings) and to make sure that you stay informed about what that dog is trained to do so you won't prevent it from performing that job. This will also prevent awkward situations, and prevent the person from feeling discriminated against. Open a door of communication so that they know they are welcome in public spaces free of judgement!
